  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "zysYqTR3oym0+kNxUnty6jHp/VA=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nSwarm **feeds** are mutable pointers built as a sequence of SOCs whose addresses are deterministically derivable from `(owner, topic, index)`.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Feed address: `Keccak256(Keccak256(topic || index) || owner_address)`\n- Topic is an arbitrary 32-byte identifier (the adapter uses `ph:v2:doc:<docId>`, `ph:v2:drive:<driveId>`, etc.)\n- Only the owner private key can publish updates; anyone knowing `owner + topic` can read\n- Typical feed payload is 8-byte timestamp + 32-byte Swarm reference\n- Two indexing schemes:\n  - **Sequential**: 0, 1, 2, ... \u2014 best for ordered updates and messaging\n  - **Epoch-based**: nested time epochs with binary search \u2014 best for sporadic/irregular updates\n- The adapter uses sequential indexing via bee-js `feedIndexNext` header auto-detection\n\n## Why it matters\n\nFeeds let Swarm support named, mutable resources despite chunks being immutable. They are the transport for every manifest update our adapter writes.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
